VESICULAR STOMATITIS: POSSIBLE VECTOR
*************************************
A ProMED-mail post
http://www.promedmail.org
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
http://www.isid.org

Date: Sun 7 Jul 2019
From: Alex I Donaldson <alex.donaldson3@virginmedia.com> [edited]


Do bats play a role in the epidemiology of vesicular stomatitis [VS]?
The spread of VS in association with watercourses has long been recognized. Watercourses provide an ecological niche for arthropods, insectivorous bats, and birds. Surveys in VS endemic regions have shown serological evidence of VSV infection both in birds and bats. Although laboratory studies have failed to show birds play a part in the epidemiology of VS, the susceptibility of bats (_Myotis lucifugus lucifugus_) to experimental infection with VSV-Indiana and the transmission of the virus from viremic bats to suckling mice by _Aedes aegypti_ mosquitoes have been demonstrated. Those laboratory results were obtained during part of my PhD and prompted me to propose bats should be considered as possible maintenance hosts for VSV [see reference below]. Unfortunately, I was not able to investigate that hypothesis but perhaps the recent outbreaks in New Mexico and Texas or those in the future will provide an opportunity.

--
Professor Alex I Donaldson
Head, Pirbright Laboratory (1989-2002)
Surrey
UK
<alex.donaldson3@virginmedia.com>

[Reference
----------
Donaldson AI. Bats as possible maintenance hosts for vesicular stomatitis virus. Am J Epidemiol. 1970; 92(2): 132-6. doi: 10.1093/oxfordjournals.aje.a121185

Dr Donaldson may have a point. This may be something the United States Department of Agriculture or a university might choose to pursue and verify.

In Panama, vesicular stomatitis virus was found to infect members of 7 mammalian orders, including opossums, xenarthrans (sloths, anteaters, and armadillos), bats, primates, carnivores, rodents, and lagomorphs (rabbits). Induced infection studies have established that a variety of wild and domestic ungulates are susceptible, including deer, horses, pigs, cattle, and sheep. Many of these wild and domestic vertebrates undoubtedly function as amplifying hosts of the virus. Because phlebotomine sand flies can transmit the virus transovarially, the flies are also potential insect reservoirs. <Fine SM. Vesicular stomatitis virus -- an overview. In Mandell, Douglas, and Bennett's Principles and Practice of Infectious Diseases: https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/B9781455748013001648. - Mod.TG]
